@node PATTERN "CSV-Tool Help:  Pattern"
@prev IMPORT
@toc FORMAT
@next EXPORT
@smartwrap
@font helvetica.font 13
@{jleft}@{lindent 8}

@{Title_Header "P A T T E R N"}
@{Title_String "Define a @{B}Pattern@{UB} as"}
@{Title_Footer "format string description."}
@{lindent 24}


There are numerous way you may want to display a number.  The
format string allows you to provide a symbolic representation of
how you want the number to appear.  The format string uses special
characters to represent a picture of how the number should look.@{par}

@{b}Examples...@{ub}@{par}

@{bold "Value"}@{tab}@{bold "Format string"}@{tab}@{tab}@{bold "Result"}@{par}
29.5@{tab}@{tab}"Total $##,###.00"@{tab}"Total $29.50"@{par}
-125.6@{tab}"_____.____"@{tab}@{tab}" -125.6   "@{par}
35437.476@{tab}"___,___,__0.00"@{tab}"     35,437.48"@{par}
-.1@{tab}@{tab}"___,___,__0.00"@{tab}"         -0.10"@{par}
4194@{tab}@{tab}"  00000 Zip Code"@{tab}"  04194 Zip Code"@{par}
45@{tab}@{tab}"+_____"@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}"  +45"@{par}
.000432@{tab}"0.0000 E+00"@{tab}@{tab}"4.3200 E-04"@{par}

@{b}Leading Sign Character (optional)@{ub}@{par}
@{tab}@{b}+@{ub} Always show the sign.@{par}
@{tab}@{b}-@{ub} Display a minus when negative.@{par}

@{b}Digit Characters@{ub}@{par}
@{tab}@{b}0@{ub} Display a Digit or a ZERO.@{par}
@{tab}@{b}#@{ub} Display a Digit or nothing.@{par}
@{tab}@{b}_@{ub} Display a Digit or space.@{par}

@{b}Separating Characters@{ub}@{par}
@{tab}@{b},@{ub} Separates Integer part with commas@{par}
@{tab}@{b}.@{ub} Aligns the decimal place@{par}
@{tab}@{b}E@{ub} Designates Exponent part ("e" is also valid)@{par}

@{b}Format string description...@{ub}@{par}
The format string must contain one or more digit characters.
These characters can be proceeded by a sign character.  The
resulting number will never display more digits than represented
in the format string.  If the number is negative and a leading
sign character was not provided, the most significant digit
character will be "borrowed" to display the negative sign.  Using
the "-" provides for a negative sign for negative numbers.  Using
the "+" causes the result to contain a sign when it is positive or
negative.@{par}

@{b}Examples...@{ub}@{par}

@{bold "Value"}@{tab}@{bold "Format string"}@{tab}@{bold "Result"}@{par}
123@{tab}@{tab}"___"@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}"123"@{par}
-2@{tab}@{tab}"___"@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}" -2"@{par}
-414@{tab}@{tab}"___"@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}"***" (overflow)@{par}
-414@{tab}@{tab}"-___"@{tab}@{tab}"-414"@{par}
2@{tab}@{tab}"-___"@{tab}@{tab}"  2"@{par}
45@{tab}@{tab}"+0000"@{tab}@{tab}"+0045"@{par}
-633@{tab}@{tab}"+0000"@{tab}@{tab}"-0633"@{par}

The Digit Characters "#", "_", and "0" provide for digits in the
number.  Leading "#" characters are disregarded when the number is
smaller than the format string.  Leading "_" characters are
changed to spaces when the number is smaller than the format
string.  Finally, the "0" is always represented.@{par}

These digit characters can be combined in the format string.
However, they cannot appear in any order.  Because the "#" means
"convert to nothing if not needed", it cannot follow a "_" or "0"
in the integer part of the format string.  For example, "___###"
is an invalid format string.  After all, how can the lesser
significant digits become nothing?@{par}

Similarly, the "_", meaning "convert to a space if not needed",
cannot follow a "0" in the integer part of the format string.@{par}

The integer part of the format string can contain "," characters.
If they are used, they must be positioned appropriately.@{par}

The Fraction portion is designated by the position of the "."  If
the decimal is omitted, it is assumed the number should be
represented as a whole number without a decimal. The same Digit
Characters are used to represent the fraction.@{par}

However, if you wish to mix the usage of the "#", "_", and "0" in
the fractional part, the order is reversed.  If a "#" is used, it
must follow "_" or "0" characters and the "_" must follow any "0"
characters.@{par}

The fractional part is rounded to fit into the number of digits
provided.@{par}

Exponential numbers can be represented using the "E" or "e"
character followed by a digit format string.  Because the exponent
format string creates a number which is left justified, the mixing
of digit characters follows the same rule as fraction digits.  The
"#" must follow "_" or "0" characters and the "_" must follow any
"0" characters.@{par}

If the number is too large to be represented in the format string,
it results in an overflow.  When an overflow is the result, "***"
is returned.@{par}

However, an alternate format string can be provided for an
overflow. Alternate format strings are separated by the "|"
character.@{par}

@{b}Examples...@{ub}@{par}

@{bold "Value"}@{tab}@{bold "Format string"}@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}@{bold "Result"}@{par}
10000@{tab}"####.##"@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}"***"@{par}
10000@{tab}"####.##|0.00E+000"@{tab}@{tab}@{tab}"1.00E+004"@{par}
.04543@{tab}"0.0000|####.##|0.00e+000"@{tab}@{tab}"0.0454"@{par}
84.1255@{tab}"0.0000|####.##|0.00e+000"@{tab}@{tab}"84.13"@{par}
35271.5@{tab}"0.0000|####.##|0.00e+000"@{tab}@{tab}"3.53e+004"@{par}

You can provide as many alternate format strings as you wish.
Each alternate format string will be evaluated until a format
string can be used.  If none are usable an overflow will result.@{par}
@{PARD}

@endnode
